{"parse":{"title":"banana","pageid":3483,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"banana\"}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n[[File:Bananavarieties.jpg|thumb|Four different types of bananas. The larger yellow bananas on the far right are commercially dominant Cavendish bananas.]]\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|en|bonana|bonano|bonanoe||all|_|obsolete}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|en|:bor|pt:banana|es:banana}}\n{{bor+|en|pt|banana}} or {{bor|en|es|banana}}, derived from a {{der|en|nic|-}} language spoken in the [[Guinea]] region.<ref>{{R:OED Online|banana|pos=n|id=28257385}}</ref> Specific derivation is {{unc|en|unclear}}. Possible ancestor or cognate languages include {{der|en|wo|banaana}}, {{der|en|emk|banana}}, and {{der|en|vai|ꕒꘌꕯ}} or {{m|vai|ꕒꕌꕯ|tr=ɓaana}},<ref>{{R:MWO}}</ref><ref>{{R:Dictionary.com}}</ref><ref>{{R:Collins}}</ref><ref>{{cite-book|page=144|url=https://archive.org/details/outlinesofgramma00koeluoft|title=Outlines of a Grammar of the Vei Language: Together with a Vei-English Vocabulary|author=S.W. Koelle|publisher=London Church Missionary House|year=1854}}</ref> possibly from {{der|en|ar|بَنَان||fingertip, banana}}.<ref>Oxford Dictionaries citing John Ayto’s The Diner’s Dictionary: Word origins of food and drink [https://web.archive.org/web/20170710073834/http://blog.oxforddictionaries.com/2014/08/origin-banana/]</ref> However, ''Ay Baati Wolof'' (Munro & Gaye, 1997) posits that {{cog|wo|banaana}} is itself derived from {{cog|pt|banana}}.<ref>{{cite-book|en|title=Ay baati Wolof: A Wolof dictionary|author=Munro, Pamela|author2=Gaye, Dieynaba|year=1997|oclc=938011184|url=https://linguistics.ucla.edu/publications/opl_19.pdf|location=Los Angeles|series=\nUCLA Occasional Papers in Linguistics|publisher=Department of Linguistics, University of California, Los Angeles|page=15}}</ref>\n\nThe racial slur derives from the notion that they are “[[yellow|Yellow]] (East-Asian) on the outside, but [[white|White]] (Westernized) on the inside”.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/bəˈnɑː.nə/|a=RP}}\n** {{audio|en|en-uk-banana.ogg}}\n\n* {{IPA|en|/bəˈnæ.nə/|a=GA}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-banana.ogg}}\n\n* {{IPA|en|/bəˈna.na/|[bɐ.näː.näˑ]|a=Indic}}\n\n* {{hyph|en|ba|na|na}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɑːnə|ænə|s=3}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q503}} An elongated curved tropical fruit of a {{vern|banana plant}}, which grows in bunches and has a creamy flesh and a smooth skin. {{defdate|from 1597}}\n#: {{ux|en|Jimmy had a '''banana''' for breakfast.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2017|author={{w|Sam Shepard}}|title=Spy of the First Person|chapter=27|url=|page=62|text=I'll need a few things. I'll need some mayonnaise and a silver tin of sardines, a '''banana'''. |isbn=9780525521563}}\n## {{lb|en|North America|UK|Ireland}} In particular, the sweet, yellow fruit of the Cavendish banana [[cultivar]], which may be eaten raw, as distinct from e.g. a [[plantain]] for cooking.\n# The tropical tree-like plant which bears clusters of bananas, a plant of the genus ''[[Musa]]'' (but sometimes also including plants from {{taxfmt|Ensete|genus}}), which has large, elongated leaves. {{defdate|from 1697}}\n# {{lb|en|uncountable}} A yellow color, like that of a banana's skin. {{defdate|from 1923}}\n#: {{color panel|FFE135}}\n# {{lb|en|pejorative|ethnic slur}} A person of [[East Asian|East]] or [[Southeast Asian]] [[descent]], [[consider]]ed to be [[overly]] [[assimilated]] and [[subservient]] to [[white]] [[authority]]. {{defdate|from 1970}}\n#: {{syn|en|Twinkie}}\n# {{lb|en|Malaysia|Singapore|pejorative|ethnic slur}} A person of [[Chinese]] descent who cannot speak [[Mandarin]] or any Chinese [[dialect]] \n# {{lb|en|slang}} The [[penis]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1986|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=_6cgAQAAMAAJ|title=Cop Feels of Three Men's \"Privates\"|author=Christopher Street|volume=10|text=The fact that the cop bought O'Brien a beer after feeling of his '''banana''' suggests that it must have been a promising one}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2012|author=Sarah Miynowski|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=lg0mATRb6EAC&pg=PT36|title=Fishbowl|page=36|text=His you-know-what turned soft .. his eight o'clock class was the last thing on his mind five minutes ago, when his '''banana''' wasn't overripe.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2014|author=Anthony Bunko|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=MdBxBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT71|title=Lord Forgive Me|page=71|text=Most of the gang were trying their best to shag the girls. One boy was sitting in a tree playing with himself and another was asking a table of teenagers if they would like to see his '''banana'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2017|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=4pQ4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA234|title=Intimate Relationships in Cinema, Literature and Visual Culture|page=234|text=He adds that after eating his '''banana''' (sucking his penis), he wants anal sex, but she asks him to lick her pussy. Then he tells her no because it is disgusting.}}\n# {{lb|en|sports}} A [[banana kick]].\n# {{lb|en|nuclear physics}} A [[banana equivalent dose]].\n# {{lb|en|computer science|colloquial}} A [[catamorphism]] (from the use of [[banana bracket]]s in the notation).\n# An incorrectly held [[handstand]], often seen in beginners.\n\n====Hypernyms====\n* {{sense|fruit}} [[Thesaurus:fruit|fruit]]\n* {{sense|Asian assimilated into Western culture}} {{l|en|race traitor}}\n\n====Hyponyms====\n* {{sense|Asian assimilated into Western culture}} {{l|en|jook-sing}}\n\n====Coordinate terms====\n* {{sense|Asian assimilated into Western culture}} {{l|en|coconut}}, {{l|en|egg}}, {{l|en|Oreo}}\n* {{sense|fruit}} {{l|en|finger}}, {{l|en|hand}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|Abyssinian banana\n|apple banana|banana tree\n|banana bag\n|banana ball\n|banana belt|red-flowering banana\n|banana-bender,banana bender\n|banana bird\n|banana boa\n|banana boat\n|banana bond\n|banana box\n|banana bread\n|banana bus\n|banana cake\n|banana chair\n|banana clip\n|banana connector|time flies like an arrow; fruit flies like a banana\n|banana cue\n|banana-ey\n|banana fly\n|banana fold\n|banana freckle\n|banana frog\n|Bananagate\n|bananageddon\n|banana hammock\n|bananahood\n|banana ketchup\n|banana knife\n|Bananaland\n|banana leaf\n|bananaless\n|banana-like\n|bananalike\n|banana lounge\n|banana lounger\n|banana melon\n|banana money\n|banana-nose\n|banana nose\n|banana note\n|banana oil\n|banana orbit\n|Banana Pancake Circuit\n|Banana Pancake Trail\n|banana paper\n|banana passionfruit\n|banana peel\n|banana pepper\n|banana-phile\n|bananaphile\n|bananaphobia\n|banana phone\n|banana plug\n|banana pose\n|banana prawn\n|banana pudding\n|bananaquit\n|banana republic\n|bananarita\n|Banana River\n|banana roll\n|bananas\n|banana seat\n|bananas Foster\n|banana shallot\n|banana-shaped\n|banana shot\n|banana skin\n|banana slice\n|banana slug\n|banana solution\n|banana spider\n|banana split\n|banana squash\n|bananatini\n|banana-y\n|banana yucca\n|bananery\n|bananivorous\n|bananoid\n|bandango\n|banilla\n|banoffee\n|banoffee pie\n|banoodles\n|Blue Banana\n|bush banana\n|Cavendish banana\n|coconana\n|don't buy green bananas\n|false banana\n|Flying Banana\n|Golden Banana\n|hairy banana\n|have one foot on a banana peel\n|if you pay bananas, you get monkeys\n|make like a banana and split\n|nonbanana\n|one-banana problem\n|pink banana\n|prairie banana\n|red banana\n|scarlet banana\n|second banana\n|snow banana\n|strawbana\n|textile banana\n|top banana\n|tough bananas\n}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|ja|バナナ|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ko|바나나|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|mnc|ᠪᠠᠨᠠᠨᠠ|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|mi|panana|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|tpi|banana|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|zu|úbhanána|bor=1}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|fruit}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Abau: {{tt|aau|yoh}}\n* Abkhaz: {{tt|ab|абанан}}\n* Afrikaans: {{tt+|af|piesang}}\n* Ahom: {{tt|aho|𑜀𑜤𑜐𑜫}}\n* Akan: {{tt|ak|akwaadu}}\n* Albanian: {{tt+|sq|banane}}\n* Amharic: {{tt+|am|ሙዝ}}\n* Amis: {{tt|ami|pawli}}\n* Angal Enen: {{tt|aoe|ai}}\n* Arabic: {{tt|ar|مَوْزَة|f}}, {{tt|ar|مَوْز|m}} {{qualifier|collective}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{tt|arz|موزة|f|tr=mōza}}, {{tt|arz|موز|m-p|tr=mōz}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{tt|acw|موزة|f|tr=mōza}}, {{tt|acw|موز|m-p|tr=mōz}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{tt|ary|بنان|m|tr=banān}}, {{tt|ary|بنانة|f|tr=banāna}}\n* Argobba: {{tt|agj|ሙዝ|tr=muz}}\n* Armenian: {{tt+|hy|բանան}}, {{tt+|hy|ադամաթուզ}}\n* Asi: {{tt|bno|batag}}\n* Assamese: {{tt|as|কল}}\n* Asturian: {{tt+|ast|plátanu|m}}, {{tt|ast|bananu|m}}, {{tt+|ast|banana|f}}\n* Atayal: {{tt|tay|buqoh}}, {{tt|tay|guquh}}\n* Aymara: {{tt+|ay|puquta}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{tt+|az|banan}}\n* Balinese: {{tt|ban|biu}}\n* Basay: {{tt|byq|puti}}\n* Basque: {{tt|eu|platano}}, {{tt+|eu|albo}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt|be|бана́н|m}}\n* Bengali: {{tt+|bn|কলা}}, {{tt+|bn|রম্ভা}}, {{tt+|bn|কদল}}\n* Bhojpuri: {{t|bho|केला}}\n* Bikol:\n*: Buhi'non Bikol: {{tt|ubl|batag}}\n*: Central Bikol: {{tt+|bcl|batag}}\n*: East Miraya Bikol: {{tt|rbl|batag}}\n*: Libon Bikol: {{tt|lbl|batag}}\n*: Northern Catanduanes Bikol: {{tt|cts|saging}}\n*: Rinconada Bikol: {{tt|bto|batag}}\n*: Southern Catanduanes Bikol: {{tt|bln|batag}}\n*: West Miraya Bikol: {{tt|fbl|batag}}\n* Binukid: {{tt|bkd|saging}}\n* Bolinao: {{tt|smk|batag}}\n* Bouyei: {{tt|pcc|joicdiangz}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt|bg|бана́н|m}}\n* Bunun: {{tt|bnn|bunbun}}\n* Burmese: {{tt|my|ငှက်ပျောသီး}}\n* Carpathian Rusyn: {{t|rue|бана́н|m}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|banana|f}}, {{tt+|ca|plàtan|m}}\n* Cebuano: {{tt|ceb|saging}}\n* Chakma: {{tt|ccp|𑄇𑄧𑄣|tr=kalā}}\n* Chamicuro: {{tt|ccc|masipata}}\n* Chavacano: {{tt|cbk|saging}}\n* Chechen: {{tt|ce|банан}}\n* Cherokee: {{tt|chr|ᏆᏁᎾ}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{tt+|yue|香蕉|tr=hoeng1 ziu1}}, {{tt|yue|蕉|tr=ziu1}}\n*: Dungan: {{tt|dng|щёнҗё}}, {{tt|dng|баҗё}}\n*: Eastern Min: {{t|cdo|芭蕉}}\n*: Gan: {{t|gan|香蕉}}\n*: Hakka: {{tt|hak|弓蕉|tr=kiûng-chêu}}\n*: Hokkien: {{tt|nan-hbl|弓蕉//芎蕉|tr=keng-chio, kin-chio, geng-chio}}, {{tt|nan-hbl|金蕉|tr=kim-tsio}}\n*: Jin: {{t|cjy|香蕉}}\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|香蕉|tr=xiāngjiāo}}\n*: Wu: {{tt|wuu|香蕉}}\n*: Xiang: {{t|hsn|香蕉}}\n* Circassian:\n*: West Circassian: {{tt|ady|бэнанэ}}\n* Coptic: {{tt|cop|ⲁⲗⲗⲱⲕⲓ}}\n* Cornish: {{tt+|kw|banana|m}}\n* Cuyunon: {{tt|cyo|saging}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|banán|m}}, {{tt+|cs|banánový}} {{qualifier|corresponding to English attributive use}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|banan|c}}\n* Dhivehi: {{tt|dv|ދޮންކެޔޮ}}\n* Dusun:\n*: Central Dusun: {{tt|dtp|punti}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|banaan|f}}, {{tt+|nl|pisang|m|f}} {{q|Netherlands|dated}}, {{tt+|nl|bacove}} {{q|Suriname}}\n* Dzongkha: {{t|dz|ངང་ལག}}\n* Enga: {{tt|enq|angató}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt+|eo|banano}}\n* Estonian: {{tt+|et|banaan}}\n* Farefare: {{t|gur|kodugu}}\n* Faroese: {{tt|fo|banan|f}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|banaani}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|banane|f}}\n* Frisian:\n*: North Frisian:\n*:: Föhr-Amrum: {{t|frr|banaan|f|n}}\n*:: Halligen: {{t|frr|banaon|f}}\n*:: Northern Goesharde: {{t|frr|banåån|f}}\n*:: Sylt: {{t|frr|Banaan|f}}\n*: West Frisian: {{tt|fy|banaan|c}}\n* Friulian: {{tt|fur|banane}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|banana|f}}\n* Georgian: {{tt|ka|ბანანი}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Banane|f}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|μπανάνα|f}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t-needed|grc}}\n* Greenlandic: {{tt|kl|banani}}\n* Guarani:\n*: Paraguayan Guarani: {{tt-check|gug|pakova}}\n* Gujarati: {{tt|gu|કેળું|n}}\n* Haitian Creole: {{tt|ht|fig}}\n* Hausa: {{tt|ha|ayaba|f}}\n* Hawaiian: {{tt|haw|maiʻa}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|בָּנָנָה|f|tr=banána}}\n* Higaonon: {{tt|mba|saging}}\n* Hiligaynon: {{tt|hil|saging}}\n* Hindi: {{tt+|hi|केला|m}}\n* Hiri Motu: {{tt|ho|biku}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|banán}}\n* Hunsrik: {{tt|hrx|Banann|f}}\n* Ibaloi: {{tt|ibl|balat}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|banani|m}}, {{tt+|is|bjúgaldin|n}} {{qualifier|very uncommon}}\n* Ido: {{tt+|io|banano}}\n* Ifugao:\n*: Batad Ifugao: {{tt|ifb|balat}}\n* Ilocano: {{tt|ilo|saba}}\n* Inabaknon: {{tt|abx|punti}}\n* Indonesian: {{tt+|id|pisang}}\n* Interlingua: {{tt+|ia|banana}}\n* Irish: {{tt|ga|banana|m}}\n* Isoko: {{tt|iso|oruvbo}}\n* Italian: {{